properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and blowing snow over the weekend ... A low pressure system will track across Southern Quebec and is expected to bring 10 to 15 centimetres of snow between Saturday afternoon and Sunday morning. Also, moderate to strong easterlies will cause local blowing snow, especially over exposed terrain such as the St Lawrence Valley. Accumulating snow and poor visibility could cause road conditions to deteriorate and make travel difficult. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall amounts expected Friday night through Saturday. An approaching low pressure system will bring snowfall the area beginning late Friday night. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A multi-day episode of very cold wind chills continues. The coldest wind chill values will be near minus 45. There will be slight moderation in temperature and wind chill over some parts of Alberta tonight under cloudy conditions. However, wind chill values will be extreme once again Friday night over most of the province as skies clear. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls continue tonight. Additional local snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm are expected with these snow squalls. Currently the strongest band is located near Grand Bend through London and is moving to the southwest. Strong winds up to 60 km/h are expected causing areas of blowing snow. Snow squalls will weaken late this evening north of Goderich but persist into early Friday morning further south. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
